            <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 tracking-tight mb-6 pb-2 border-b border-slate-100">
              How to Verify AI Research
            </h2>
            <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
              To ensure the accuracy and integrity of your research, always follow these four verification guidelines:
            </p>

            <div class="space-y-4 text-sm text-slate-600">
              <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-sm mb-1">1. Verify DOIs and Citations</h4>
                <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed text-slate-500">
                  Always copy the DOI (Digital Object Identifier) or paper title cited by the AI and verify it directly on academic search engines like Crossref, PubMed, or Google Scholar. If the citation does not exist on these databases, do not use it.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-sm mb-1">2. Read the Full Text</h4>
                <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed text-slate-500">
                  AI engines typically summarize paper abstracts, which can occasionally omit critical details about study limitations, population sizes, or conflict of interest declarations. Always read the methodology and conclusion sections of the full text before citing a paper.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-sm mb-1">3. Evaluate the Journal Quality</h4>
                <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed text-slate-500">
                  Ensure the cited paper is published in a reputable, peer-reviewed journal. Check the journal's indexing on databases like Scopus or SCImago to verify it is not a predatory publication.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-sm mb-1">4. Analyze the Sample Size</h4>
                <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed text-slate-500">
                  When citing medical or psychological findings, check the study's participant sample size ($N$) and control group parameters. A study with a small sample size ($N &lt; 30$) may not represent a consensus, even if it is cited as a finding by the AI.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </section>

          <!-- Common Mistakes Section -->
          <section id="common-mistakes" class="mt-16 scroll-mt-20">
            <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 tracking-tight mb-6 pb-2 border-b border-slate-100">
              Common Mistakes to Avoid
            </h2>
            <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
              Avoid these four common pitfalls when using AI for research:
            </p>

            <ul class="space-y-4 text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              <li class="flex gap-2">
                <span class="text-rose-500 shrink-0">⚠️</span>
                <div>
                  <strong>Citing Hallucinated Sources:</strong> Do not copy bibliographies generated by general models (like ChatGPT or Claude) without verifying them. General models predict word sequences rather than query verified databases.
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-2">
                <span class="text-rose-500 shrink-0">⚠️</span>
                <div>
                  <strong>Ignoring Paywalled Literature:</strong> AI research engines typically search public indexes. Skimming only open-access papers can bias your literature review; ensure you also search paywalled journals through library subscriptions.
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-2">
                <span class="text-rose-500 shrink-0">⚠️</span>
                <div>
                  <strong>Uploading Sensitive Data:</strong> Avoid uploading unreleased designs, proprietary research datasets, or personal data to cloud-based AI tools unless you have verified their data privacy agreements.
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-2">
                <span class="text-rose-500 shrink-0">⚠️</span>
                <div>
                  <strong>Overlooking Research Methodology:</strong> Do not cite a finding without checking the study type. A randomized controlled trial (RCT) provides stronger scientific evidence than an observational survey, even if both are cited similarly by the AI.
                </div>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </section>

